05":"1005","1059":"1059","16 Sep 1083":"16 september 1083","Beaumont, Dordogne, Aquitaine, France":"Beaumont-du-Périgord, Dordogne, Aquitaine, Frankrijk","Rouen, Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France":"Rouen, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, Frankrijk","Cambrai, Nord, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Cambrai, Noorderdepartement, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Frankrijk","Cumberland, England":"Cumberland, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1040–11 July 1091":"about 1040–11 July 1091","1040–1091":"1040–1091","1040–1140":"1040–1140","1059–1150":"1059–1150","1005–1083":"1005–1083","1008–1099":"1008–1099","1091":"1091","about 1040":"about 1040","11 July 1091":"11 July 1091","1099":"1099","Bef 1059":"before 1059","1140":"1140","1150":"1150","1040":"1040","1083":"1083","1008":"1008","1005":"1005","1059":"1059","16 Sep 1083":"16 September 1083","Beaumont, Dordogne, Aquitaine, France":"Beaumont-du-Périgord, Dordogne, Aquitaine, France","Rouen, Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France":"Rouen, Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France","Cambrai, Nord, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Cambrai, Nord, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France","Cumberland, England":"Cumberland, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Beaumont","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Gilles, Gaetan, Honore, Jacques, Jean-Guy, Marcel.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of the five places in Normandy or several others elsewhere in France so named. The placename comes from Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>mont</i> ‘hill’. There are also places in England so named under Norman influence in Cumberland, Lancashire, and Essex, the last of which changed its name in the 12th century from <i>Fulepet</i> ‘foul pit’ to <i>Bealmont</i> ‘beautiful hill’; these may also have given rise to the surname. The surname is now widespread throughout England, but most common in Yorkshire. Compare   Belmont  .","History: Many English bearers of this surname are descended from Henry de Beaumont (died 1340), who came to England from France as a soldier, serving Kings Edward I, II, and III of England. He acquired the earldom of Buchan in Scotland by marriage. — Many American bearers of this surname are descendants of John Beaumont (1612–47), who came to North America from England in 1630. William Beaumont came from England to Cambridge MA in 1635 and subsequently moved to CT."],"variants":[{"name":"Bement","meanings":["English (Cambridgeshire): variant of   Beaumont  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Beeman","meanings":["English (Kent): occupational name for a beekeeper, from Middle English <i>bee-man</i> ‘bee-keeper’ (Old English <i>bēo</i> + <i>mann</i>).","English (Kent): variant of   Beaumont  .","Americanized form of German   Biemann   or of its Dutch cognate <b>Bieman</b>."]},{"name":"Belmont","meanings":["French and English (of Norman origin): variant of   Beaumont  .","Catalan: habitational name from the placename Bellmont ‘beautiful mountain’. Compare Spanish   Belmonte  ."]},{"name":"Baumunk","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Siegmund.","German: probably a Germanized form of a French Huguenot name <b>Beaumont</b> (see also   Beaumont  )."]},{"name":"Bayman","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire): variant of   Beaumont  .","Americanized form of German <b>Beumann</b> or <b>Bäumann</b>, variants of   Baumann  ."]}]},{"name":"Beatrix","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Late Latin personal name, which was borne by a saint martyred in Rome, together with Saints Faustinus and Simplicius, in the early 4th century. The original form of the name was probably <i>Viatrix</i>, a feminine version of <i>Viator</i> ‘voyager (through life)’, which was a favourite name among early Christians. This was then altered by association with Latin <i>Beatus</i> ‘blessed’ (<i>Via-</i> and <i>Bea-</i> sometimes being pronounced the same in Late Latin).  See also  Beatrice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Beatrix de Beaumont was born about 1040, in Cambrai, Nord, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France, her father, Yves Beaumont III, was 36 and her mother, Judith Adela Degourney, was 33. She married Michael Fleming before 1059. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died on 11 July 1091, in Rouen, Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France, at the age of 52, and was buried in Rouen, Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France."},"et":{"about 1040–11 July 1091":"umbes 1040–11. juuli 1091","1040–1091":"1040–1091","1040–1140":"1040–1140","1059–1150":"1059–1150","1005–1083":"1005–1083","1008–1099":"1008–1099","1091":"1091","about 1040":"umbes 1040","11 July 1091":"11. juuli 1091","1099":"1099","Bef 1059":"enne 1059","1140":"1140","1150":"1150","1040":"1040","1083":"1083","1008":"1008","1005":"1005","1059":"1059","16 Sep 1083":"16. september 1083","Beaumont, Dordogne, Aquitaine, France":"Beaumont-du-Périgord, Dordogne, Aquitaine, Prantsusmaa","Rouen, Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France":"Rouen, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Cambrai, Nord, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Cambrai, Nord, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Pr